00:07:35.550 --> 00:07:37.640
to speak about the story.

00:07:37.640 --> 00:07:43.580
The story of the looted literary
treasures and the looted books

00:07:43.580 --> 00:07:47.460
of the Holocaust that comprises
such an important and as we said,

00:07:47.460 --> 00:07:51.960
as Sharon said, largely unknown
chapter of Holocaust history.

00:07:51.960 --> 00:07:54.610
There are many ways we
could tell the story

00:07:54.610 --> 00:07:56.560
of the looted books
of the Holocaust.

00:07:56.560 --> 00:07:59.990
We could start the story
in many different places.

00:07:59.990 --> 00:08:06.590
I like to start it in a snowy day
in February in late February 1946,

00:08:06.590 --> 00:08:10.790
almost exactly 70 years
ago in Hamburg in Germany.

00:08:10.790 --> 00:08:15.670
It was evidently a snowy
and blizzardy day that day

00:08:15.670 --> 00:08:20.290
and at the airport arrived
a young man by the name

00:08:20.290 --> 00:08:27.950
of let me see how I can make this
work here Captain Seymour Pomrenze.

00:08:27.950 --> 00:08:29.990
Seymour Pomrenze was
a fascinating man.

00:08:29.990 --> 00:08:34.990
An Orthodox Jewish archivist who
had been doing some work in Germany

00:08:34.990 --> 00:08:37.510
on some of the material
that had been discovered,

00:08:37.510 --> 00:08:40.880
and he had been summoned to
Frankfurt, and he was picked

00:08:40.880 --> 00:08:44.370
up at the airport by a man named
Lieutenant Lesley Post [phonetic]

00:08:44.370 --> 00:08:49.050
who began to drive him across
the Main River towards a suburb

00:08:49.050 --> 00:08:51.180
of Frankfurt called Offenbach.

00:08:51.180 --> 00:08:55.970
And on the way he explained there
was some material that the allies,

00:08:55.970 --> 00:08:59.140
that the allied forces had
discovered as the war was ending

00:08:59.140 --> 00:09:02.680
that he had been assigned
to sort through

00:09:02.680 --> 00:09:05.850
and Lieutenant Post evidently
was out of his league

00:09:05.850 --> 00:09:07.150
in sorting through this stuff.

00:09:07.150 --> 00:09:09.990
He was, he went on to be
an accomplished scholar

00:09:09.990 --> 00:09:11.890
but at this point he was very young

00:09:11.890 --> 00:09:14.600
and he was having trouble
just dealing

00:09:14.600 --> 00:09:17.940
with what he had to deal with.

00:09:17.940 --> 00:09:22.920
They drove across the Main River
and they went to they soon arrived

00:09:22.920 --> 00:09:26.280
at a warehouse that had
belonged before the war

00:09:26.280 --> 00:09:28.990
to the IG Farben chemical company.

00:09:28.990 --> 00:09:32.310
This was a company that among
other things manufactured some

00:09:32.310 --> 00:09:36.570
of the component elements to
Zyklon B gas, the gas that was used

00:09:36.570 --> 00:09:40.200
in the gas chambers in Nazi
Europe, and now it's being used

00:09:40.200 --> 00:09:43.980
to house some recovered
Jewish material.

00:09:43.980 --> 00:09:49.950
Pomrenze walks into this building,
the what would soon be known

00:09:49.950 --> 00:09:54.440
as the Offenbach Archival Depot
and he couldn't believe what he saw

00:09:54.440 --> 00:09:58.660
because there in front
of him was an ocean

00:09:58.660 --> 00:10:02.290
of books, an ocean of material.

00:10:02.290 --> 00:10:06.650
It reminds me do you remember that
final scene at the end of Raiders

00:10:06.650 --> 00:10:10.210
of the Lost Ark that scene where
he's in the warehouse and just row

00:10:10.210 --> 00:10:13.240
after row after row of
boxed up, well here you had

00:10:13.240 --> 00:10:16.460
that except it's not so
neatly stored as it was there.

00:10:16.460 --> 00:10:19.050
You had this chaos of material.

00:10:19.050 --> 00:10:22.350
He took one look at it and
realized that he was looking

00:10:22.350 --> 00:10:26.400
at the literary ruins of a lost
civilization, of a civilization

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:28.070
that had just been destroyed.

00:10:28.070 --> 00:10:30.990
He was astounded and he said
he almost felt like crying.

00:10:30.990 --> 00:10:34.530
He didn't know how he was
going to possibly deal

00:10:34.530 --> 00:10:36.960
with all of this material.

00:10:36.960 --> 00:10:42.000
Well, he soon got to work and he
created what was officially known

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:44.760
as I said a moment ago as
the Offenbach Archival Depot.

00:10:44.760 --> 00:10:49.060 position:56%
He hired a staff of a couple hundred
German citizens as well as a few

00:10:49.060 --> 00:10:52.870 position:56%
of his military advisors and they
began sorting through this material.

00:10:52.870 --> 00:10:54.900
They divided it into
three categories;

00:10:54.900 --> 00:10:56.840 position:56%
first was the identifiable material,

00:10:56.840 --> 00:11:01.810
that material whose ownership
before the war was readily evident

00:11:01.810 --> 00:11:07.870 position:56%
and where they could they restituted
the books to their original owners.

00:11:07.870 --> 00:11:10.660
He was kind of limited because
there was this principle,

00:11:10.660 --> 00:11:14.450
there's a legal principle
known as escheat which says

00:11:14.450 --> 00:11:19.040 position:56%
that he can only restitute war booty

00:11:19.040 --> 00:11:21.730
to governments and
not to individuals.

00:11:21.730 --> 00:11:27.490
So they would send huge shipments
out to Holland to other countries

00:11:27.490 --> 00:11:30.980
where they knew that their national
libraries had been the original

00:11:30.980 --> 00:11:32.430
owners of this material.

00:11:32.430 --> 00:11:35.420
There was also the semi
identifiable material,

00:11:35.420 --> 00:11:40.810
material that might have a mark
on it that seemed to indicate

00:11:40.810 --> 00:11:44.410
where it was from but there
was no definitive proof

00:11:44.410 --> 00:11:46.360
or perhaps there was
a person's name on it

00:11:46.360 --> 00:11:48.410
but they didn't know what
happened to that person.

00:11:48.410 --> 00:11:50.580
And then there was a
great deal of the material

00:11:50.580 --> 00:11:52.730
that was completely unidentifiable.

00:11:52.730 --> 00:11:58.680
So they began going through
this material and as they did,

00:11:58.680 --> 00:12:05.680
Captain Pomrenze took note of what
he was dealing with and started

00:12:05.680 --> 00:12:08.240
to ask himself how
all this happened.

00:12:08.240 --> 00:12:13.850
He knew along with the rest
of the world that Nazis early

00:12:13.850 --> 00:12:16.450
in the war had another
way of dealing

00:12:16.450 --> 00:12:20.070
with their looted literary
material which was what?

00:12:20.070 --> 00:12:21.370
&gt;&gt; Burning.

00:12:21.370 --> 00:12:22.670
&gt;&gt; Rabbi Mark Glickman:
Burning them.

00:12:22.670 --> 00:12:28.640
And he had heard the reports
from May 1933 of this huge rash

00:12:28.640 --> 00:12:31.650
of Jewish book burnings
but what he didn't realize,

00:12:31.650 --> 00:12:34.970
what I certainly didn't realize at
the beginning of this research was

00:12:34.970 --> 00:12:38.580
that while the Nazis did
burn books at the beginning

00:12:38.580 --> 00:12:41.100
of the war they only
did so for a short time.

00:12:41.100 --> 00:12:42.840
The book burnings only lasted

00:12:42.840 --> 00:12:46.860
for the most part during a
three week period in May 1933.

00:12:46.860 --> 00:12:51.050
They were a way for Hitler to
sort of establish his toehold

00:12:51.050 --> 00:12:53.840
in the German cultural imagination

00:12:53.840 --> 00:12:56.820
because these book burnings
were great spectacles

00:12:56.820 --> 00:13:00.140
and there were fire chants,
and there were incantations,

00:13:00.140 --> 00:13:04.480
and there were fiery speeches and
then they had these big bonfires.

00:13:04.480 --> 00:13:09.030
What many people didn't realize and
certainly has been forgotten now is

00:13:09.030 --> 00:13:12.480
that those book burnings
they didn't work really well.

00:13:12.480 --> 00:13:16.640
First of all, it's
hard to burn a book.

00:13:16.640 --> 00:13:21.710
Books, physically it's
hard to burn a book.

00:13:21.710 --> 00:13:25.450
Books burn far more like logs
than they do like kindling,

00:13:25.450 --> 00:13:29.030
so if you throw a book into if you
try to touch a match or something

00:13:29.030 --> 00:13:32.080
to a book, it's not going
to catch fire very easily.

00:13:32.080 --> 00:13:34.810
We have accounts of people
whose books were thrown

00:13:34.810 --> 00:13:39.610
into these bonfires one night,
going out there the next morning,

00:13:39.610 --> 00:13:43.460
picking the books up and brushing
the ashes off and taking them home.

00:13:43.460 --> 00:13:47.430
And it's also figuratively
speaking, it's hard to burn a book

00:13:47.430 --> 00:13:50.900
because in the age of printing of
course if you burn one copy or even

00:13:50.900 --> 00:13:53.160
if you burn a hundred copies
of a book there are going

00:13:53.160 --> 00:13:58.050
to be other copies
around in other places.

00:13:58.050 --> 00:14:01.440
Helen Keller was one of the
authors whose books were burned

00:14:01.440 --> 00:14:05.790
and she said you are fools if
you think you can destroy ideas.

00:14:05.790 --> 00:14:09.940
So sometimes you can destroy
a few copies of a bound book

00:14:09.940 --> 00:14:12.960
but you can't destroy
the book itself

00:14:12.960 --> 00:14:15.600
because the book itself
is going to survive.

00:14:15.600 --> 00:14:20.300
Aside from that, the book burnings
brought the Nazis really bad press.

00:14:20.300 --> 00:14:25.950
They were seen in the international
media as thugs and oafs

00:14:25.950 --> 00:14:29.860
for having done this if you
can believe such a thing.

00:14:29.860 --> 00:14:32.620
They, the books many
of them were chosen

00:14:32.620 --> 00:14:35.990
because there had been a black
list of prohibited authors

00:14:35.990 --> 00:14:38.470
that had been published
before the book burnings

00:14:38.470 --> 00:14:43.370
so they could have some guidelines
as to what material to confiscate

00:14:43.370 --> 00:14:45.920
and there were authors
around the world

00:14:45.920 --> 00:14:48.670
who were complaining
of being white listed.

00:14:48.670 --> 00:14:54.620
They were complaining that
they weren't on the list

00:14:54.620 --> 00:14:58.640
and the worldwide press
really just excoriated Germany

00:14:58.640 --> 00:14:59.940
for doing this thing.

00:14:59.940 --> 00:15:01.480
And of course they
were looking forward

00:15:01.480 --> 00:15:04.620
in 33 they were already
looking forward to a big event

00:15:04.620 --> 00:15:08.820
that was going to happen in
Germany in 1936 which was what?

00:15:08.820 --> 00:15:10.120
&gt;&gt; The Olympics.

00:15:10.120 --> 00:15:11.420
&gt;&gt; Rabbi Mark Glickman:
The Olympics,

00:15:11.420 --> 00:15:12.930
and they knew that if they
were still doing such things

00:15:12.930 --> 00:15:14.670
when the Olympics came to town

00:15:14.670 --> 00:15:17.120
that it would not look
good on the world stage.

00:15:17.120 --> 00:15:19.180
So quickly the book
burnings stopped.

00:15:19.180 --> 00:15:24.430 position:56%
They flared up again if you will a
couple years later a few years later

00:15:24.430 --> 00:15:26.900 position:56%
in Kristallnacht at the end of 1938,

00:15:26.900 --> 00:15:32.580
but for the most part this was
just a brief spade of book burnings

00:15:32.580 --> 00:15:36.870
that the happened in 1933.

00:15:36.870 --> 00:15:40.940
In the late 1930s Hitler
was approached by one

00:15:40.940 --> 00:15:45.080
of his main ideologues one
of the main intellectuals

00:15:45.080 --> 00:15:50.680
in the Nazi regime, a Nazi
soldier, a Nazi official

00:15:50.680 --> 00:15:55.180
with the unlikely name
of Alfred Rosenberg.

00:15:55.180 --> 00:15:59.580
Rosenberg was an intellectual
if you could call him that.

00:15:59.580 --> 00:16:02.840
It was probably more like
a pseudo intellectual.

00:16:02.840 --> 00:16:06.740
He wrote a book of the Myth
of the Twentieth Century

00:16:06.740 --> 00:16:09.940
which was the second best
selling book in all Germany.

00:16:09.940 --> 00:16:15.110
Second of course only to Mein
Kampf and it was this 800 page,

00:16:15.110 --> 00:16:19.930
7 or 800 page tome with thousands
of footnotes and apparently

00:16:19.930 --> 00:16:23.480
if you were the kind of
person who would fail

00:16:23.480 --> 00:16:28.350
to see the emperor's new
clothes, you would have admitted

00:16:28.350 --> 00:16:31.050
that this was an impossible
piece of work to read.

00:16:31.050 --> 00:16:34.830
It was kind of like remember
the book A Brief History

00:16:34.830 --> 00:16:37.060
of Time by Steven Hawking?

00:16:37.060 --> 00:16:39.480
Everybody had this book on
their shelves when it came out,

00:16:39.480 --> 00:16:43.870
nobody I think ever understood a
word of what he was saying in there

00:16:43.870 --> 00:16:45.430
but it looked great on the shelf.

00:16:45.430 --> 00:16:49.220
And so too did the far
more voluminous Myth

00:16:49.220 --> 00:16:51.970
of the Twentieth Century.

00:16:51.970 --> 00:16:55.620
Rosenberg was a rising
star in the Nazi regime.

00:16:55.620 --> 00:16:59.100
He was not in Hitler's inner circle
but he was trying to get there.

00:16:59.100 --> 00:17:01.490
He was eventually put in
charge of the territories,

00:17:01.490 --> 00:17:03.690
the conquered territories
in the east,

00:17:03.690 --> 00:17:07.320
but he was also an intellectual and
we went up to Hitler and he knew

00:17:07.320 --> 00:17:11.670
that Hitler had long dreamed of
opening Hauptschule an institute

00:17:11.670 --> 00:17:14.360
for higher learning that
would really be a testament

00:17:14.360 --> 00:17:18.050
to the great intellectual
achievement of German civilization.

00:17:18.050 --> 00:17:22.530
And he went to Hitler and he said
my Fuhrer, why don't you allow me

00:17:22.530 --> 00:17:25.040
to start to build these
institutions?

00:17:25.040 --> 00:17:28.620
And how about a part of it is an
institute for Jewish research?

00:17:28.620 --> 00:17:32.150
Let's open in fact a series of
institutes for Jewish research

00:17:32.150 --> 00:17:36.260
after the war to study
this extinct Jewish people?

00:17:36.260 --> 00:17:39.100
The Jewish people of course will
soon be extinct and it's going

00:17:39.100 --> 00:17:42.160
to be important for the world
to know just like we know

00:17:42.160 --> 00:17:45.580
about other extinct civilizations,
it will be important for the world

00:17:45.580 --> 00:17:50.230
to know what this civilization
was about and who to teach them

00:17:50.230 --> 00:17:54.210
who can teach the world about
this extinct civilization

00:17:54.210 --> 00:17:59.310
if not the great Nazi, Nazi regime.

00:17:59.310 --> 00:18:03.050 position:56%
And so Hitler gave him permission to
build these institutes and Rosenberg

00:18:03.050 --> 00:18:06.900
and of course if we're going to
have these institutes we're going

00:18:06.900 --> 00:18:10.100 position:56%
to need some libraries, and if we're
going to have libraries we're going

00:18:10.100 --> 00:18:12.750 position:56%
to need to put books in the library.

00:18:12.750 --> 00:18:19.160
So Hitler gave Rosenberg
permission to gather books

00:18:19.160 --> 00:18:24.880
from the conquered
territories of the Nazi regime.

00:18:24.880 --> 00:18:29.140 position:56%
When the Nazis would take over a new
territory, he would be able to go

00:18:29.140 --> 00:18:33.050
and take and confiscate
some Jewish books.

00:18:33.050 --> 00:18:36.400
But of course in the late 1930s
there weren't many conquered

00:18:36.400 --> 00:18:41.880
territories, but in 1940 in May
of 1940 Germany invaded and took

00:18:41.880 --> 00:18:45.130
over France and it was like
a treasure chest opened

00:18:45.130 --> 00:18:47.160
up before Alfred Rosenberg's eyes

00:18:47.160 --> 00:18:50.250
because of course throughout
France particularly in Paris

00:18:50.250 --> 00:18:53.430
but elsewhere there were all
kinds of Jewish libraries,

00:18:53.430 --> 00:18:56.990
private libraries, institutional
libraries that had been abandoned

00:18:56.990 --> 00:19:00.510
by Jews who were fleeing
Nazi oppression.

00:19:00.510 --> 00:19:05.580
And it was very easy for
Rosenberg to go in and to take

00:19:05.580 --> 00:19:08.090
over the material that
was in that library.

00:19:08.090 --> 00:19:13.040
He created what was called the
Einsatzstab Reichsleiter Rosenberg,

00:19:13.040 --> 00:19:18.110
the Rosenberg task force
otherwise known as the ERR.

00:19:18.110 --> 00:19:19.560
When you study this especially

00:19:19.560 --> 00:19:21.710
if you don't know German
it's a challenge

00:19:21.710 --> 00:19:24.930
to return these multisyllabic
German words.

00:19:24.930 --> 00:19:28.830
He created the ERR which went
out and went to these libraries

00:19:28.830 --> 00:19:31.390
and confiscated the material
and originally it was all sent

00:19:31.390 --> 00:19:33.730
to Frankfurt, it was
stored elsewhere

00:19:33.730 --> 00:19:36.280
as well as the war went on.

00:19:36.280 --> 00:19:40.920
And he established a routine
where the Nazis would go in

00:19:40.920 --> 00:19:43.290
and they would take over a
town and this was especially

00:19:43.290 --> 00:19:46.740
so as the Nazis went into Poland
and Russia and other places

00:19:46.740 --> 00:19:52.240
in Eastern Europe and the routine
was a simple if not tragic one.

00:19:52.240 --> 00:19:56.100 position:56%
The Nazis would go into a town, they
would empty that town of its Jews,

00:19:56.100 --> 00:19:59.790
the Jews would be taken out to
the outskirts of town sometimes

00:19:59.790 --> 00:20:05.150
and shot right there or loaded
up into cattle cars and taken off

00:20:05.150 --> 00:20:07.700
for execution in one
of the death camps.

00:20:07.700 --> 00:20:11.460
And shortly after that the ERR guys
would go in and they would load

00:20:11.460 --> 00:20:14.760
up the Jewish books from the
homes, from the libraries,

00:20:14.760 --> 00:20:18.330 position:56%
from the synagogues, from the
schools and they would take them off

00:20:18.330 --> 00:20:22.110
to a collecting point
somewhere nearby.

00:20:22.110 --> 00:20:24.640
We'll get to those
collecting points in a while.

00:20:24.640 --> 00:20:29.540
And soon the library, the
Nazi Jewish library grew.

00:20:29.540 --> 00:20:32.680
Rosenberg was not the
only one collecting books

00:20:32.680 --> 00:20:37.540
under the leadership of another man
named Reinhard Heydrich even more

00:20:37.540 --> 00:20:38.840
books were collected.

00:20:38.840 --> 00:20:41.530
These were collected from
within Germany itself.

00:20:41.530 --> 00:20:44.130
Rosenberg was collecting
them outside Germany,

00:20:44.130 --> 00:20:49.490
Heydrich was collecting them
from within the territories

00:20:49.490 --> 00:20:51.850
from within the lands of
the Third Reich itself.

00:20:51.850 --> 00:20:56.530
He was able to unify all of the
various German police forces,

00:20:56.530 --> 00:21:00.250
security forces into
one single organization.

00:21:00.250 --> 00:21:03.850
In my book by the way I compare
the Nazi organizational chart

00:21:03.850 --> 00:21:08.070
to a Jackson Pollock painting
with a German language overlay

00:21:08.070 --> 00:21:12.810
to understand the way
the Nazi regime was setup

00:21:12.810 --> 00:21:15.490
and to understand these various
agencies and what they did

00:21:15.490 --> 00:21:19.820
and who they reported
to is a gargantuan task,

00:21:19.820 --> 00:21:22.510
but what Heydrich was able
to do was to take many

00:21:22.510 --> 00:21:26.710
of these security institutions
with overlapping responsibilities

00:21:26.710 --> 00:21:32.610
and unify them now to talk
about multisyllabic German words

00:21:32.610 --> 00:21:35.310
into the Reichssicherheitshauptamt.

00:21:35.310 --> 00:21:38.780 position:56%
And if you knew how long it took me
to learn how to pronounce that word.

00:21:38.780 --> 00:21:43.700
The Reich Security Main Office,
the RSHA and he too started

00:21:43.700 --> 00:21:47.590
to collect books in a similar
way to the way Rosenberg did.

00:21:47.590 --> 00:21:52.490
There were other Nazi organizations
that were doing the same thing,

00:21:52.490 --> 00:21:56.130
and so again they would go into
towns and once that were emptied

00:21:56.130 --> 00:21:58.560
of their Jews, they
would collect the books.

00:21:58.560 --> 00:22:00.630
They sent them to collecting points

00:22:00.630 --> 00:22:05.310
and often these collecting points
were in monasteries and in castles

00:22:05.310 --> 00:22:08.950
and in warehouses throughout
the territories

00:22:08.950 --> 00:22:10.720
that the Nazis had taken over.

00:22:10.720 --> 00:22:13.740
So there were books stored
in the Von Pless Castle,

00:22:13.740 --> 00:22:18.300
there were books stored
here in the Tworkow Castle,

00:22:18.300 --> 00:22:21.160
dozens of places these
books were stored.

00:22:21.160 --> 00:22:24.860
They were even stored in the
famous Neuschwanstein Castle.

00:22:24.860 --> 00:22:27.240 position:56%
Most of the material that was stored

00:22:27.240 --> 00:22:29.830
in Neuschwanstein was
the looted artwork

00:22:29.830 --> 00:22:33.780
but there were books
stored there as well.

00:22:33.780 --> 00:22:39.820
As the war went on it became more
and more difficult to keep them

00:22:39.820 --> 00:22:41.120
in some of these storage places

00:22:41.120 --> 00:22:43.000
because the storage places
themselves were taken

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:48.640
over as the size of the Reich's
land holdings began to shrink.

00:22:48.640 --> 00:22:52.320
And so slowly there began to
consolidate the collections

00:22:52.320 --> 00:22:56.720
and in Eastern Europe most
of the material was sent

00:22:56.720 --> 00:23:01.020
to a town called Rotibor or
there's a way to pronounce

00:23:01.020 --> 00:23:04.750
that in modern Polish that I'm not
going to even try to pronounce.

00:23:04.750 --> 00:23:08.580
Here use see is a stockpile
in Rotibor and then

00:23:08.580 --> 00:23:13.390
in Germany they were sent to a town
called Hungen and they were stored

00:23:13.390 --> 00:23:15.300
in the castle and in
other places there.

00:23:15.300 --> 00:23:21.070
These two towns were, you
know, typically when you think

00:23:21.070 --> 00:23:23.530
of a storage facility
you think of a warehouse

00:23:23.530 --> 00:23:24.980
or a building of some sort.

00:23:24.980 --> 00:23:29.510
These were entire towns as the
volume of the material grew,

00:23:29.510 --> 00:23:32.830
these became entire towns
whose every public building

00:23:32.830 --> 00:23:36.630
for the most part was devoted
to storing this material.

00:23:36.630 --> 00:23:40.130
So the bank building would
have material, the church,

00:23:40.130 --> 00:23:43.820
the community center
would all be filled

00:23:43.820 --> 00:23:46.260
with these materials
in these two towns.

00:23:46.260 --> 00:23:52.430
There were storage places elsewhere
too but the two largest ones were

00:23:52.430 --> 00:23:56.570
in Hungen and in Rotibor as well.

00:23:56.570 --> 00:24:00.840
We're going to come back to
Schloss Hungen in a little while.

00:24:00.840 --> 00:24:06.320
So to look at the contrast between
1933 and 1943 is astounding.

00:24:06.320 --> 00:24:10.560
In 1933 as you've seen we had this.

00:24:10.560 --> 00:24:19.130
These orgies of book burning but
by 1943 it had moved to this.

00:24:19.130 --> 00:24:22.910
To Nazi soldiers and officials
going through this material,

00:24:22.910 --> 00:24:25.420
sorting it out, trying
to organize it

00:24:25.420 --> 00:24:28.100
and again the amount was just huge.

00:24:28.100 --> 00:24:31.130
They were only able to
organize a small amount of it

00:24:31.130 --> 00:24:35.340
but they did what they
did what they could.

00:24:35.340 --> 00:24:38.140
Now not all the books
went by the way we have

00:24:38.140 --> 00:24:41.810
until one o'clock including
Q and A, is that correct?

00:24:41.810 --> 00:24:43.240
Including Q and okay.

00:24:43.240 --> 00:24:53.650
So not the books went readily
to their into Nazi hands,

00:24:53.650 --> 00:25:01.780
and one story that is important
to tell are the books of Vilna.

00:25:01.780 --> 00:25:04.180
Vilna which was now
Vilnius the capital

00:25:04.180 --> 00:25:07.850
of Lithuania was a teeming
Jewish community before the war.

00:25:07.850 --> 00:25:09.710
Tens of thousands of
Jews lived there

00:25:09.710 --> 00:25:12.660
and there were Jewish
theaters, and Jewish newspapers,

00:25:12.660 --> 00:25:18.140
and schools of all kinds,
and even in its area

00:25:18.140 --> 00:25:22.870
around Vilna there was an
active and vibrant Jewish life.

00:25:22.870 --> 00:25:26.950
When the Nazis took Vilna over,
they went into Vilna itself

00:25:26.950 --> 00:25:28.270
and all the towns around Vilna

00:25:28.270 --> 00:25:30.870
and again they collected
the Jewish books.

00:25:30.870 --> 00:25:36.160
And originally they sent them to
the university to be sorted through

00:25:36.160 --> 00:25:42.420 position:56%
and processed but eventually they
realized that that didn't make sense

00:25:42.420 --> 00:25:46.070
because outside of the Vilna
Ghetto there is a library,

00:25:46.070 --> 00:25:48.550
there was a building
that had belonged

00:25:48.550 --> 00:25:52.420
to YIVO the Jewish scientific
institute, an organization

00:25:52.420 --> 00:25:55.010
that before the war had
been documenting the history

00:25:55.010 --> 00:25:56.430
of Eastern European Jewry.

00:25:56.430 --> 00:26:00.060
They had a huge library there
already and so it made sense

00:26:00.060 --> 00:26:04.710
to send all the books to this one
library to get sorted through.

00:26:04.710 --> 00:26:08.840
The man in charge of the effort
was a man named Johannes Pohl

00:26:08.840 --> 00:26:11.940
and here we should step back
and take note of the fact

00:26:11.940 --> 00:26:17.390
that there was a cadre, there
was a phenomenon during the war

00:26:17.390 --> 00:26:20.940
of Nazi Judaic scholars.

00:26:20.940 --> 00:26:26.320
This is also an untold story
largely of World War II was

00:26:26.320 --> 00:26:31.960
that the Nazi regime was
able to boast of many people

00:26:31.960 --> 00:26:36.910
who were trained experts in Judaica
who knew Hebrew, who knew Talmud,

00:26:36.910 --> 00:26:42.160
who knew Jewish history and they
used that knowledge in a variety

00:26:42.160 --> 00:26:47.280 position:56%
of ways in order to further the anti
Semitic aims of the Nazi regime.

00:26:47.280 --> 00:26:49.660
So here you have this
man Johannes Pohl

00:26:49.660 --> 00:26:54.180 position:56%
who before the war had studied
Jewish studies for a couple of years

00:26:54.180 --> 00:26:58.440 position:56%
at the Hebrew University in
Jerusalem and now he's put in charge

00:26:58.440 --> 00:27:03.120
of processing this
material in Vilna.

00:27:03.120 --> 00:27:08.170
So what he did was he conscripted
a few dozen Jewish literati

00:27:08.170 --> 00:27:10.180
from the Vilna Ghetto.

00:27:10.180 --> 00:27:14.830
These were poets, these were
historians, these were writers

00:27:14.830 --> 00:27:18.220
of different kinds and
every day this group

00:27:18.220 --> 00:27:24.240 position:56%
of people would be marched out of
the Vilna Ghetto to the YIVO Library

00:27:24.240 --> 00:27:25.810
where they would be
assigned the task

00:27:25.810 --> 00:27:27.310
of sorting through this material.

00:27:27.310 --> 00:27:30.500
Since there was so much of it they
were told that they should sort

00:27:30.500 --> 00:27:34.960
through it and only keep the
most valuable 20 to 30 percent

00:27:34.960 --> 00:27:38.910
of what they saw and the rest of it
was going to go to the pulp mill.

00:27:38.910 --> 00:27:42.570
And it's a very interesting
story, therefore,

00:27:42.570 --> 00:27:46.810
I have these books being
gathered, being collected

00:27:46.810 --> 00:27:51.000
in a central gathering place,
being marched past an official

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:54.260
for a cursory examination,
some books go one way,

00:27:54.260 --> 00:27:57.780
some books go the other way and
depending on which way they go,

00:27:57.780 --> 00:28:01.670
that will determine whether they
have a chance of surviving the war.

00:28:01.670 --> 00:28:04.190
And in that sense of course
the story of the books

00:28:04.190 --> 00:28:08.520
of the Holocaust is eerily
parallel to that of the people

00:28:08.520 --> 00:28:12.940
of the Holocaust although
of course far less tragic.

00:28:12.940 --> 00:28:17.360
So these scholars, these people
who love books who used to study

00:28:17.360 --> 00:28:20.740
in the YIVO Library before the war
and now were being brought there

00:28:20.740 --> 00:28:24.310
and with every book that was put
in their hands they had an option.

00:28:24.310 --> 00:28:28.990
Either destroy it or
give it to the Nazis.

00:28:28.990 --> 00:28:33.070
And often they were able with great
difficulty and with having gone

00:28:33.070 --> 00:28:36.730
and with great pain they were
able to make that decision

00:28:36.730 --> 00:28:40.200
but sometimes they couldn't
stomach either of those decisions.

00:28:40.200 --> 00:28:43.120
So what they started to do
was when they came across some

00:28:43.120 --> 00:28:46.570
of the really valuable
material, they would put it aside

00:28:46.570 --> 00:28:50.260
and at the end of the day they
would hide it in their clothing

00:28:50.260 --> 00:28:55.070
and bring it back with them into
the ghetto for safe keeping.

00:28:55.070 --> 00:28:59.980
It is to me ironic that inside
the ghetto itself was seen

00:28:59.980 --> 00:29:01.970
as the safest place
for these books to be.

00:29:01.970 --> 00:29:06.480
That's where they could keep their
eyes on them, and so you would see

00:29:06.480 --> 00:29:10.050
at the end of the day if you look
closely all of these scholars

00:29:10.050 --> 00:29:14.080
and poets and writers walking out
of the YIVO Library with puffed

00:29:14.080 --> 00:29:17.060
up clothes because there were
these books inside trying

00:29:17.060 --> 00:29:19.350
to sneak them back into the ghetto.

00:29:19.350 --> 00:29:22.620
At one point somebody
said, are you crazy?

00:29:22.620 --> 00:29:24.590
Are you nuts?

00:29:24.590 --> 00:29:28.300
They're books, you're
risking your lives for books.

00:29:28.300 --> 00:29:31.180
And one of the members
of this group said, well,

00:29:31.180 --> 00:29:35.550
books you know they
don't just grow on trees.

00:29:35.550 --> 00:29:40.720
The group called itself the Paper
Brigade and soon they realized

00:29:40.720 --> 00:29:44.310
that this process was going far
too slowly, that they needed

00:29:44.310 --> 00:29:47.130
to speed things up if they were
going to save anything close

00:29:47.130 --> 00:29:49.770
to the number of books
that they hoped to save.

00:29:49.770 --> 00:29:51.930
And they realized that the guard

00:29:51.930 --> 00:29:57.750
at the YIVO facility the Polish
guard was an untrained almost deaf

00:29:57.750 --> 00:30:03.090 position:56%
guy who felt badly about the fact
that he was an uneducated guy and so

00:30:03.090 --> 00:30:05.380
out of the kindness of their
hearts a couple members

00:30:05.380 --> 00:30:10.270
of the Paper Brigade volunteered to
tutor him at lunchtime every day,

00:30:10.270 --> 00:30:13.740
and while they did
so, the other members

00:30:13.740 --> 00:30:17.230
of the Paper Brigade busied
themselves taking as many books

00:30:17.230 --> 00:30:21.090
as they could and hiding them above
the ceiling and behind the walls

00:30:21.090 --> 00:30:23.080
of the YIVO building hoping

00:30:23.080 --> 00:30:26.650
that they would last
there until after the war.

00:30:26.650 --> 00:30:30.400
One of the main members of this,
one of the most well known members

00:30:30.400 --> 00:30:41.660
of the Paper Brigade was a poet
by the name of Avraham Sutzkever.

00:30:41.660 --> 00:30:45.280
He and Shmerke Kaczerginski they
were both the only two people

00:30:45.280 --> 00:30:47.280
who survived until after the war.

00:30:47.280 --> 00:30:50.570
Sometimes at lunchtime or on breaks

00:30:50.570 --> 00:30:53.800
in their work Avraham
Sutzkever would sit down

00:30:53.800 --> 00:30:59.650
and write poetry reflecting on his
life and reflecting on his world

00:30:59.650 --> 00:31:03.750
when he was working in the
YIVO facility and in one

00:31:03.750 --> 00:31:08.900
of the poems he wrote he used an
image that Ann Brener is Ann here?

00:31:08.900 --> 00:31:14.750
Ann there's Ann was able to
help me unpack a little bit.

00:31:14.750 --> 00:31:17.470
Apparently in medieval poetry,
and Ann you'll correct me

00:31:17.470 --> 00:31:21.520
if I'm wrong I hope, they
use the image was often used

00:31:21.520 --> 00:31:24.120
of the word as black pearls.

00:31:24.120 --> 00:31:29.440
The words were seen as black
pearls on the page and in a poem

00:31:29.440 --> 00:31:34.990
that he wrote, Sutzkever
used that image.

