as a burnt pearl on the body

00:31:41.860 --> 00:31:45.690
of on the charred remains
of a woman's body.

00:31:45.690 --> 00:31:50.760
We don't have the owner of the
pearls left and all that remains

00:31:50.760 --> 00:31:55.710 position:56%
of her are the burnt pearls that she
once wore, and he used that image

00:31:55.710 --> 00:32:00.680
as a way of looking at
the words around him

00:32:00.680 --> 00:32:04.390
that the owner's bodies themselves
were being charred and all

00:32:04.390 --> 00:32:07.700
that is remaining now are
the burnt pearls, the books,

00:32:07.700 --> 00:32:10.810
the written words themselves.

00:32:10.810 --> 00:32:15.940
One other story, a couple
of these stories of how some

00:32:15.940 --> 00:32:18.500
of the books survived
are fascinating.

00:32:18.500 --> 00:32:22.200
There is a book a very famous book
called the Sarajevo Haggadah a

00:32:22.200 --> 00:32:26.200
beautiful Passover Haggadah that
was made originally in Spain

00:32:26.200 --> 00:32:31.000
and spirited out we think when the
Jews were expelled in Spain in 1492

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:35.790
and eventually made its
way to Sarajevo in Bosnia

00:32:35.790 --> 00:32:38.440
and it's a beautiful
illuminated book.

00:32:38.440 --> 00:32:42.210
Here you see a picture of a
facsimile edition of the book

00:32:42.210 --> 00:32:44.220
that I have in my own library.

00:32:44.220 --> 00:32:49.250
When the Nazis took over
Sarajevo early on they went one

00:32:49.250 --> 00:32:53.480
of the Nazi officials went to the
Bosnian national museum in order

00:32:53.480 --> 00:32:57.650
to get the Sarajevo Haggadah
and he walked in and he asked

00:32:57.650 --> 00:33:00.650
to see the library director and
he was introduced to the director.

00:33:00.650 --> 00:33:03.640
The director didn't speak
any German so they called

00:33:03.640 --> 00:33:07.110
on a man named Dervis Korkut
to serve as an interpreter.

00:33:07.110 --> 00:33:13.140
Dervis Korkut was a young Muslim
scholar who had done research

00:33:13.140 --> 00:33:16.280
in a variety of different
fields and he was able to help

00:33:16.280 --> 00:33:19.690
because he knew German and he
knew the local language as well

00:33:19.690 --> 00:33:24.260
and was able to help translate, and
the Nazi official said I've come

00:33:24.260 --> 00:33:27.840
to get the Sarajevo
Haggadah, and the director

00:33:27.840 --> 00:33:29.230
of the museum said, I'm sorry sir.

00:33:29.230 --> 00:33:33.660
One of your colleagues came
this morning, I give it to him.

00:33:33.660 --> 00:33:36.420
He said who was my colleague
who came this morning?

00:33:36.420 --> 00:33:38.990
He said I didn't think it was
appropriate for me to ask his name.

00:33:38.990 --> 00:33:41.500
He said so you don't have
the Sarajevo Haggadah here?

00:33:41.500 --> 00:33:44.820
No, it left this morning.

00:33:44.820 --> 00:33:47.210
And so this German soldier
as I picture him he kind

00:33:47.210 --> 00:33:50.940
of clicked his heels and with an
upset look on his face he kind

00:33:50.940 --> 00:33:55.420
of turned and walked crisply
out of the room not realizing

00:33:55.420 --> 00:34:00.070
that during the entire conversation
the famous Sarajevo Haggadah had

00:34:00.070 --> 00:34:02.960
been hidden in Dervis
Korkut's pants.

00:34:02.960 --> 00:34:07.820
He had put it in the waistband of
his pants to hide it from the Nazi

00:34:07.820 --> 00:34:14.790
and he and the head of the museum
had colluded right before this talk

00:34:14.790 --> 00:34:17.460
in order to make sure that
they saved his Haggadah.

00:34:17.460 --> 00:34:20.920
And they were able to save it
for the duration of the war

00:34:20.920 --> 00:34:23.770 position:56%
and it still exists now in Sarajevo.

00:34:23.770 --> 00:34:26.270 position:56%
What is important to note as well is

00:34:26.270 --> 00:34:29.610
that the Sarajevo Haggadah
was not the only book

00:34:29.610 --> 00:34:32.550
that Dervis Korkut was
not the only thing rather

00:34:32.550 --> 00:34:36.750
that Dervis Korkut saved from
Nazi hands during the war.

00:34:36.750 --> 00:34:42.210
He was also able to help rescue
a young Jewish woman who showed

00:34:42.210 --> 00:34:45.940
up bedraggled and in great need
of safe haven at his doorstep

00:34:45.940 --> 00:34:49.220
and at great risk to his
life and to that of his wife,

00:34:49.220 --> 00:34:51.240
the couple was able to shelter her

00:34:51.240 --> 00:34:53.790
until she could get somewhere
safer during the war.

00:34:53.790 --> 00:34:56.430
So this was really a heroic man.

00:34:56.430 --> 00:35:00.420
We can also tell the story of
a young couple Hans Augusto

00:35:00.420 --> 00:35:03.190
and Margaret Reyersbach, a
young couple that had met

00:35:03.190 --> 00:35:06.010
in Brazil, German Jewish couple.

00:35:06.010 --> 00:35:14.680
He was in advertising and she
was an artist and they started

00:35:14.680 --> 00:35:20.030
to on the side make children's
books originally in Brazil.

00:35:20.030 --> 00:35:24.570
They took their honeymoon in the
late 30s to Paris and they fell

00:35:24.570 --> 00:35:27.820 position:56%
in love with and were enchanted by
the city and like many people who go

00:35:27.820 --> 00:35:29.630
to Paris they found
themselves stuck.

00:35:29.630 --> 00:35:31.960
They couldn't leave
they loved it so much.

00:35:31.960 --> 00:35:35.330
And while they were there they
made some children's books.

00:35:35.330 --> 00:35:38.210
They started to create
this character named Fifi.

00:35:38.210 --> 00:35:43.200 position:56%
Fifi was this mischievous monkey who
would get into all kinds of trouble.

00:35:43.200 --> 00:35:46.050
Right before the Nazis
invaded Paris,

00:35:46.050 --> 00:35:48.840
they realized that they
needed to get out of town,

00:35:48.840 --> 00:35:50.830
so they cobbled together
a couple of bicycles,

00:35:50.830 --> 00:35:53.960
they took the Fifi drawings and
a few other personal belongings,

00:35:53.960 --> 00:35:56.040
put them on the back of their
bicycles because they knew

00:35:56.040 --> 00:35:59.140
that the Nazis this was
artwork, this was a book that was

00:35:59.140 --> 00:36:01.020
in the making, they knew
that the Nazis were going

00:36:01.020 --> 00:36:03.060
to take this if they
weren't careful.

00:36:03.060 --> 00:36:05.890
And on their cobbled together
bicycles they road out of Paris

00:36:05.890 --> 00:36:09.020
and they eventually got on trains
and they went through Spain

00:36:09.020 --> 00:36:11.810
and Portugal and then they
eventually went back to Brazil

00:36:11.810 --> 00:36:14.190
and after that they came
to the United States

00:36:14.190 --> 00:36:21.650
where they changed their names
from Hans Augusto Reyersbach

00:36:21.650 --> 00:36:26.160
and Margaret Reyersbach
to H.A. and Margaret Rey

00:36:26.160 --> 00:36:29.100
and Fifi they changed
Fifi's name as well.

00:36:29.100 --> 00:36:31.140
Does anybody know what
Fifi's name became?

00:36:31.140 --> 00:36:32.440
&gt;&gt; Curious George.

00:36:32.440 --> 00:36:39.160
&gt;&gt; Fifi became Curious George, so
Curious George was among the books

00:36:39.160 --> 00:36:44.040
that slipped through Nazi
hands during the war.

00:36:44.040 --> 00:36:49.460
When the war ended, the
allied forces went in

00:36:49.460 --> 00:36:51.640
and found this material and so

00:36:51.640 --> 00:36:55.880
when we see Schloss Hungen
again there was a young soldier

00:36:55.880 --> 00:37:02.600
by the name of Robert Schaumburg
[assumed spelling] who had grown

00:37:02.600 --> 00:37:07.280 position:56%
up in Vienna and was an attorney
there but had to flee and on his way

00:37:07.280 --> 00:37:10.310
out he said that he wasn't ever
going to come back to Europe again.

00:37:10.310 --> 00:37:13.160
And when he came to the United
States and his draft board found

00:37:13.160 --> 00:37:15.960
out that he was fluent
in six languages,

00:37:15.960 --> 00:37:21.490
before he could say Anschluss he
was back on boat back to Europe.

00:37:21.490 --> 00:37:28.540
And he was assigned a detail of
soldiers one day in 1945 or 1946

00:37:28.540 --> 00:37:35.590 position:56%
and he was sent to check out some
reclaimed material at Schloss Hungen

00:37:35.590 --> 00:37:40.300 position:56%
at the Hungen Castle which was
remember Hungen was one of the towns

00:37:40.300 --> 00:37:42.430
where all this material was sent.

00:37:42.430 --> 00:37:45.320
And he went up to the castle
and I think it was dark

00:37:45.320 --> 00:37:48.240
and as I picture it it was a
dark and dreary day that day

00:37:48.240 --> 00:37:53.060
with bats flying around the
castle, and he knocked on the door

00:37:53.060 --> 00:37:55.950
and it turns out that the owner

00:37:55.950 --> 00:37:59.350
of the castle Princess
Schloss Braunfels,

00:37:59.350 --> 00:38:04.510
Princess Solms Braunfels rather,
was no longer living in the castle.

00:38:04.510 --> 00:38:07.400
She had to flee earlier in the
war because it was discovered

00:38:07.400 --> 00:38:09.590
that she had been trying
to help some Jews.

00:38:09.590 --> 00:38:11.100
However, her husband,

00:38:11.100 --> 00:38:15.400
her octogenarian husband was still
allowed to live in the castle.

00:38:15.400 --> 00:38:18.590 position:56%
His name was James Pitcairn Knowles.

00:38:18.590 --> 00:38:22.140
He was a Scottish portrait painter

00:38:22.140 --> 00:38:24.030
and he lived there all
alone in the castle.

00:38:24.030 --> 00:38:26.900
It was just him and
Alfred the butler.

00:38:26.900 --> 00:38:30.240
And Alfred the butler, and
I'm not making this up,

00:38:30.240 --> 00:38:34.360
Alfred the butler was also an
octogenarian doddering old man.

00:38:34.360 --> 00:38:37.600
He had been involved in the
service industry for a long time

00:38:37.600 --> 00:38:43.400
and several decades earlier,
he had been a ship steward

00:38:43.400 --> 00:38:48.420
who was assigned the task of
knocking on the door of the Astors

00:38:48.420 --> 00:38:51.970
and the Guggenheims telling them
it was time to get to the deck

00:38:51.970 --> 00:38:55.610
of the Titanic immediately because
the ship was about to go down.

00:38:55.610 --> 00:39:01.590
He was that guy, and now he's
the butler in Schloss Hungen.

00:39:01.590 --> 00:39:03.630
So Schoenfeld [phonetic] goes
up and knocks on the door,

00:39:03.630 --> 00:39:08.180
Alfred the butler opens the
door and kind of says well,

00:39:08.180 --> 00:39:11.240
we've been expecting
you, come on in.

00:39:11.240 --> 00:39:14.000
And they walk in and were
astounded at what they saw

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:16.750
because throughout this entire
castle and we're only seeing part

00:39:16.750 --> 00:39:21.270
of the castle here in this picture,
floor to ceiling were bookshelves.

00:39:21.270 --> 00:39:23.490
Here the books were
perfectly organized

00:39:23.490 --> 00:39:27.770
and the whole castle was filled
with them, millions of books

00:39:27.770 --> 00:39:29.780
that had made their way there.

00:39:29.780 --> 00:39:34.930
And Alfred said, you may want
to see what's in the basement.

00:39:36.260 --> 00:39:39.750
And he took out a skeleton key,
opened the door to the basement

00:39:39.750 --> 00:39:45.010
and they walked down and there they
found huge boxes with the library

00:39:45.010 --> 00:39:49.890
of Le Corps Rabbinique the
rabbinical academy in Paris

00:39:49.890 --> 00:39:56.510
with priceless old books and
other manuscripts of all kinds.

00:39:56.510 --> 00:39:59.620
And then Alfred said, you might
want to see what's over here

00:39:59.620 --> 00:40:02.280
and he beckoned them over
to a cabinet and he takes

00:40:02.280 --> 00:40:05.950
out another skeleton
key, opens it up.

00:40:05.950 --> 00:40:09.930
It was the Rothchild's library in
there some of the great treasures

00:40:09.930 --> 00:40:11.520
from the Rothchild collection.

00:40:11.520 --> 00:40:15.440
Incunables, some of the earliest
printed Jewish books that existed

00:40:15.440 --> 00:40:17.820
and there were manuscripts
and all kinds

00:40:17.820 --> 00:40:20.190
of other priceless Jewish material.

00:40:20.190 --> 00:40:23.010
This happened place
after place after place

00:40:23.010 --> 00:40:24.610
as this material was collected.

00:40:24.610 --> 00:40:28.240
As we said it was originally
sent to Offenbach

00:40:28.240 --> 00:40:31.070
where the American army
had to figure out what

00:40:31.070 --> 00:40:32.640
to do with this material.

00:40:32.640 --> 00:40:38.290 position:56%
They restituted what material they
could but even as the war was coming

00:40:38.290 --> 00:40:41.750
to an end, they had hundreds and
hundreds and hundreds of thousands

00:40:41.750 --> 00:40:44.550
of remaining volumes not
sure what to do with it.

00:40:44.550 --> 00:40:48.580
And the issue quickly became a
political one even amongst Jews it

00:40:48.580 --> 00:40:51.600
became political, if
you can imagine that.

00:40:51.600 --> 00:40:57.940
So the Jews in the soon to be
born state of Israel were saying,

00:40:57.940 --> 00:41:00.560
you know, we are the capital
of the Jewish people here.

00:41:00.560 --> 00:41:03.760
This material should come to the
Hebrew University in Jerusalem,

00:41:03.760 --> 00:41:06.680
we'll take care of it like
nobody else can or will.

00:41:06.680 --> 00:41:10.330
And Jews in the United States were
saying our community is now the

00:41:10.330 --> 00:41:12.680
largest Jewish community
in the world.

00:41:12.680 --> 00:41:13.980
The books should come here.

00:41:13.980 --> 00:41:16.740
They should come to places like
the Library of Congress and some

00:41:16.740 --> 00:41:18.810
of the fine universities
we have here.

00:41:18.810 --> 00:41:21.150
We can take care of them
like nobody else can.

00:41:21.150 --> 00:41:24.730
And the survivors who were
staying in Europe were saying,

00:41:24.730 --> 00:41:26.870
no the books should stay here.

00:41:26.870 --> 00:41:31.200
The books should stay at home, and
can you imagine what you would do

00:41:31.200 --> 00:41:36.280
if you were in the American army
and you found that some books came

00:41:36.280 --> 00:41:40.270
from a town library, you knew
exactly where they came from

00:41:40.270 --> 00:41:43.370
but that town that Jewish
community was no longer there.

00:41:43.370 --> 00:41:46.370
Or if only or if there
were a huge library

00:41:46.370 --> 00:41:48.860
and only ten people
from that town survived.

00:41:48.860 --> 00:41:52.920 position:56%
Or what do you do with the books if
a large number had survived but half

00:41:52.920 --> 00:41:56.360 position:56%
of the people had gone to Israel and
half had come to the United States?

00:41:56.360 --> 00:41:57.660
What do you do with it then?

00:41:57.660 --> 00:41:59.770 position:56%
So there were all kinds of decisions

00:41:59.770 --> 00:42:03.090
and it was becoming this
very heated political issue

00:42:03.090 --> 00:42:06.630 position:56%
and the poor American army is
caught in the cross fire between all

00:42:06.630 --> 00:42:08.880
of these groups of bickering Jews.

00:42:08.880 --> 00:42:14.560
To their great fortune, eventually
1949 the occupation of Germany came

00:42:14.560 --> 00:42:20.010
to an effective conclusion
and as Sharon said earlier,

00:42:20.010 --> 00:42:25.020
the books were then turned over
to a team of Jewish historians

00:42:25.020 --> 00:42:28.940
and other intellectuals
called Jewish Cultural

00:42:28.940 --> 00:42:30.840
Reconstruction Incorporated.

00:42:30.840 --> 00:42:35.050 position:56%
This was an American based
organization that became the trustee

00:42:35.050 --> 00:42:38.060
of the Jewish people to
deal with this material.

00:42:38.060 --> 00:42:41.880
The director was a prominent
historian named Salo Baron

00:42:41.880 --> 00:42:45.980
at Columbia University and for a
time the on the ground director

00:42:45.980 --> 00:42:51.500
in Europe was none other than the
famous Jewish political philosopher

00:42:51.500 --> 00:42:52.800
Hannah Arendt.

00:42:52.800 --> 00:42:57.750
She spent a few years in Germany
dealing with this material and even

00:42:57.750 --> 00:43:01.760
in the most prominent
biographies that have been written,

00:43:01.760 --> 00:43:04.350
Hannah Arendt barely merits a blip

00:43:04.350 --> 00:43:07.140
in the biographies
that are told of her.

00:43:07.140 --> 00:43:11.080
But this was a major part of
her life and what she did.

00:43:11.080 --> 00:43:14.310
They too had to figure out
what to do with this material

00:43:14.310 --> 00:43:17.260
and eventually they
came up with a formula.

00:43:17.260 --> 00:43:19.890
It was their 40, 40, 20 formula.

00:43:19.890 --> 00:43:23.500 position:56%
Forty percent of the books that they
couldn't identify whose owners they

00:43:23.500 --> 00:43:27.730
couldn't identify whose provenance
was unclear, they sent to libraries

00:43:27.730 --> 00:43:31.960
in Israel, 40 percent they sent
to libraries in the United States,

00:43:31.960 --> 00:43:37.220
and 20 percent they sent elsewhere,
and the elsewhere was places

00:43:37.220 --> 00:43:41.410
like South Africa and Australia
and Argentina and libraries there.

00:43:41.410 --> 00:43:46.980
They sent many of the books to DP
camps early on so that the people

00:43:46.980 --> 00:43:49.350
in those camps could use them
but eventually then they had

00:43:49.350 --> 00:43:52.920
to decide what to do with them
after the DP camps closed.

00:43:52.920 --> 00:43:57.640 position:56%
Jewish Cultural Reconstruction
existed at least on paper until 1977

00:43:57.640 --> 00:44:02.310
and there was through the into
the early 1950s there was a lot

00:44:02.310 --> 00:44:04.960
of material that they had to deal
with and there was just a trickle

00:44:04.960 --> 00:44:06.480
that they had to deal
with afterwards

00:44:06.480 --> 00:44:11.660
but it finally closed its
doors in the late 1970s.

00:44:11.660 --> 00:44:15.370
Now, keeping my eye on the
time, it's easy to get lost

00:44:15.370 --> 00:44:19.350
in the big numbers here and I found
that it's helpful to tell the story

00:44:19.350 --> 00:44:24.720
of one book that was part of the
story to see how it really panned

00:44:24.720 --> 00:44:26.350
out in terms of that one book.

00:44:26.350 --> 00:44:30.810
And I thought we would take
a book called Hilchot Alfasi,

00:44:30.810 --> 00:44:35.420
it was written by a man named Rabbi
Isaac Alfasi whose name literally

00:44:35.420 --> 00:44:37.680
means Isaac the guy from Fes.

00:44:37.680 --> 00:44:45.060 position:56%
He was from Fes, Morocco home of the
tasseled kind of dorky looking hat,

00:44:45.060 --> 00:44:50.510
and he in the 11th
century he and some

00:44:50.510 --> 00:44:55.140 position:56%
of his colleagues were becoming
concerned because Islam was starting

00:44:55.140 --> 00:44:57.090
to shimmer pretty brightly.

00:44:57.090 --> 00:45:01.250
Islam was becoming a
temptation for Jews

00:45:01.250 --> 00:45:10.930
because it was this brilliant very
rich thriving intellectual corpus

00:45:10.930 --> 00:45:16.690
of material and it was hard
for rabbis to prevent people

00:45:16.690 --> 00:45:19.910
from converting to Islam
because at the time in order

00:45:19.910 --> 00:45:25.490
to study Judaism there were only
really for the most part two books

00:45:25.490 --> 00:45:29.760
that you could offer people who
wanted to learn about Judaism.

00:45:29.760 --> 00:45:33.070
Those two books were what?

00:45:33.070 --> 00:45:36.610
The Torah and the Talmud, and aside

00:45:36.610 --> 00:45:39.700
from that I mean there were some
other rabbinic works but the Torah

00:45:39.700 --> 00:45:42.050
and the Talmud were
about it in terms

00:45:42.050 --> 00:45:45.450
of practically available material

00:45:45.450 --> 00:45:47.790
that students of Judaism
could study.

00:45:47.790 --> 00:45:51.850
And the Talmud is a very
difficult book to study.

00:45:51.850 --> 00:45:56.600
It's in Aramaic for one thing,
it's in very terse language,

00:45:56.600 --> 00:46:01.950
it's governed by a lot of arcane
principles, and so it was very hard

00:46:01.950 --> 00:46:05.480
for rabbis like Alfasi and his
colleagues to say you should stay

00:46:05.480 --> 00:46:09.370
with Judaism and here's this great
rich literary heritage we have

00:46:09.370 --> 00:46:10.670
to offer you.

00:46:10.670 --> 00:46:13.880
So what he did, what Alfasi did
was he went to through the Talmud

00:46:13.880 --> 00:46:17.800
and he took out and kept
just the stuff that was

00:46:17.800 --> 00:46:20.700
of practical use for
Jews those days.

00:46:20.700 --> 00:46:24.460 position:56%
There's a lot of stuff in the Talmud
about sacrifices in the temple,

00:46:24.460 --> 00:46:25.760
doesn't even exist anymore.

00:46:25.760 --> 00:46:27.060
He took all that stuff out.

00:46:27.060 --> 00:46:29.330
He took out all the material
about the back and forth

00:46:29.330 --> 00:46:32.240
between the arguing and
bickering rabbis of the Talmud,

00:46:32.240 --> 00:46:35.650
all that was left out, and he
kept just the stuff that was

00:46:35.650 --> 00:46:39.590
of practical use, and he took
the 20 volume Talmud and he sort

00:46:39.590 --> 00:46:44.230
of condensed it into a three
volume Reader's Digest version

00:46:44.230 --> 00:46:45.750
of the Talmud if you will.

00:46:45.750 --> 00:46:51.470
And Hilchot Alfasi the laws
of Rabbi Alfasi was one

00:46:51.470 --> 00:46:54.360
of the very first printed
books ever.

00:46:54.360 --> 00:46:57.380
It was printed in Spain
in the late 1400s

00:46:57.380 --> 00:47:00.740
and there was a version printed
in Constantinople not long

00:47:00.740 --> 00:47:04.110
after that there were several
versions printed in Italy.

00:47:04.110 --> 00:47:07.890
The tenth time a printing house
got around to printing it it was

00:47:07.890 --> 00:47:12.780
in the town of Sulzbach in
Germany and that was in the 1760s.

00:47:12.780 --> 00:47:14.280
There was one volume that came

00:47:14.280 --> 00:47:19.210
out in 1763 another in
64 and another in 65.

00:47:19.210 --> 00:47:21.320
So we can picture say
the second volume

00:47:21.320 --> 00:47:25.470
of this book rolling
off the presses in 1764.

00:47:25.470 --> 00:47:28.240
Most of the people who studied
these books back then lived

00:47:28.240 --> 00:47:32.740 position:56%
in Eastern Europe but they were hard
to print because a page of Talmud

00:47:32.740 --> 00:47:35.430
and a page of all these
books has different fonts

00:47:35.430 --> 00:47:37.300
and there's different text blocks

00:47:37.300 --> 00:47:40.130
and it's very difficult
to layout the printing.

00:47:40.130 --> 00:47:43.880
And in Eastern Europe for the most
part they didn't have the resources

00:47:43.880 --> 00:47:48.170
to do this kind of printing and so
these books were typically printed

00:47:48.170 --> 00:47:51.260
in Western Europe but
read in Eastern Europe.

00:47:51.260 --> 00:47:53.510
So we can picture this
book second volume

00:47:53.510 --> 00:47:56.780
of Alfasi coming off the press
and being loaded by a bunch

00:47:56.780 --> 00:48:01.350
of big brawny guys out to the
back of a truck or a wagon rather.

00:48:01.350 --> 00:48:05.190
That wagon heading eastward and
we can picture it then arriving

00:48:05.190 --> 00:48:09.250
in some small town in Poland, being
taken off the truck and purchased

00:48:09.250 --> 00:48:13.400
by a book distributor who the
next day starts to make his rounds

00:48:13.400 --> 00:48:18.110
and he goes to a little town and
he shows up at the Beth Midrash,

00:48:18.110 --> 00:48:21.160
the adult study house in that
town where he's warmly greeted

00:48:21.160 --> 00:48:25.670
by the rabbi, he walks in
carrying a big pile of books,

00:48:25.670 --> 00:48:29.890
he comes out with a far shorter
pile because he just sold our copy

00:48:29.890 --> 00:48:31.980
of the second volume
of Hilchot Alfasi,

00:48:31.980 --> 00:48:35.400
the Laws of Rabbi Alfasi
to this Beth Midrash.

00:48:35.400 --> 00:48:39.150
The following day a group of
students, young students come in

00:48:39.150 --> 00:48:42.420
and they break up into pairs which
is the way they would study back

00:48:42.420 --> 00:48:47.570
in the yeshiva in the Beth Midrash
and one pair of students came

00:48:47.570 --> 00:48:49.470
across a question and
they decided they wanted

00:48:49.470 --> 00:48:52.880 position:56%
to consult the Laws of Rabbi Alfasi.

00:48:52.880 --> 00:48:56.500 position:56%
So they go to the shelf and they
pull this book off, they open it up,

00:48:56.500 --> 00:48:58.590
they study it, they put it back.

00:48:58.590 --> 00:49:01.430
The next day the same thing
happens except a different group

00:49:01.430 --> 00:49:03.810
of students takes the book
off the shelf, opens it up,

00:49:03.810 --> 00:49:05.720
studies it and puts it back.

00:49:05.720 --> 00:49:09.390
This happens day after day, month
after month, year after year

00:49:09.390 --> 00:49:13.950
for almost two centuries it sits
on the shelf of that Beth Midrash

00:49:13.950 --> 00:49:19.900
until one day the students
don't come in because

00:49:19.900 --> 00:49:24.190
of course the students early
that morning had been rounded up

00:49:24.190 --> 00:49:28.850
and taken outside to the outskirts
of town and they were all shot.

00:49:28.850 --> 00:49:33.030
And the day after that the
doors do open and instead

00:49:33.030 --> 00:49:37.590
of eager young students the
darkness comes in and a group

00:49:37.590 --> 00:49:41.780 position:56%
of Nazi soldiers enters the building
and takes our copy of Alfasi

00:49:41.780 --> 00:49:45.470 position:56%
and all the other books they find
and throws it in the back of a truck

00:49:45.470 --> 00:49:46.830
where it's taken to a castle

00:49:46.830 --> 00:49:49.460
where it's stored somewhere
until after the war.

00:49:49.460 --> 00:49:53.150
Discovered after the war, sent
to Offenbach, they open it up

00:49:53.150 --> 00:49:54.450
and they find that the stamp

00:49:54.450 --> 00:49:57.260
of that Beth Midrash while it
was still there it had faded away

00:49:57.260 --> 00:49:59.930
so much they couldn't tell
where it was originally from.

00:49:59.930 --> 00:50:03.260
So they kept it and
eventually the army turned it

00:50:03.260 --> 00:50:05.990
over to Jewish Cultural
Reconstruction who at the end

00:50:05.990 --> 00:50:10.670 position:56%
of the war put it into their 40,
40, 20 formula and sent it to Israel

00:50:10.670 --> 00:50:12.640
where it was purchased by the
library of the chief [inaudible]

00:50:12.640 --> 00:50:16.470
of Israel and it sat on the
self there for several decades

00:50:16.470 --> 00:50:20.480
until they needed to clear some
space in their library and they,

00:50:20.480 --> 00:50:23.800
what librarians call
deacquisitioned the book.

00:50:23.800 --> 00:50:28.770
They sold it off to an antiquarian
book dealer who purchased it

00:50:28.770 --> 00:50:31.880
and put it up online where it
was purchased by a customer

00:50:31.880 --> 00:50:39.910
in Washington State and here it is.

00:50:39.910 --> 00:50:42.830
So this is a book that I purchased.

00:50:42.830 --> 00:50:48.280
I purchased it the way most rabbis
purchase books these days on eBay,

00:50:48.280 --> 00:50:52.730
and when I got the book I
opened it up and I found

00:50:52.730 --> 00:50:56.780
on the inside was a
bookplate Jewish Cultural

00:50:56.780 --> 00:50:58.600
Reconstruction Incorporated.

00:50:58.600 --> 00:51:01.630
At the time I had no idea what
Jewish Cultural Reconstruction

00:51:01.630 --> 00:51:05.340
Incorporated was so I did
what most rabbis do when faced

00:51:05.340 --> 00:51:10.590
with such conundra [phonetic],
Googled it, and that sent me

00:51:10.590 --> 00:51:17.960
on to this whole story that
where wrote the book about.

00:51:17.960 --> 00:51:23.670
If only of course we had the
people who owned this but we don't.

00:51:23.670 --> 00:51:26.030
And among the only
physical relics we have

00:51:26.030 --> 00:51:29.380
of them are the books
that they left behind.

00:51:29.380 --> 00:51:38.570
It reminds me of the words of
Abraham Sutzkever who died in 2010

00:51:38.570 --> 00:51:40.950
and he wrote, it is not
just because my words quiver

00:51:40.950 --> 00:51:45.390
like broken hands grasping for aid
or that they sharpen themselves

00:51:45.390 --> 00:51:47.920
like teeth on the prowl
in the darkness,

00:51:47.920 --> 00:51:51.980
that you my written words
substitute for my world flare

00:51:51.980 --> 00:51:54.060
up the coals of my anger.

00:51:54.060 --> 00:51:57.830
It is because your sounds glint
like burnt pearls discovered

00:51:57.830 --> 00:52:03.310
in an extinguished pyre and
no one not even I shredded

00:52:03.310 --> 00:52:07.470
by time can recognize the
woman drenched in flame for all

00:52:07.470 --> 00:52:13.010
that remains of her now are those
gray pearls smoldering in the ash.

00:52:13.010 --> 00:52:15.720
All that remains of them
now are these gray pearls.

00:52:15.720 --> 00:52:21.380
But it is what we have and God
willing we can open the books again

00:52:21.380 --> 00:52:26.120
and let the pearls shine forth
for us all to see in the future.

00:52:26.120 --> 00:52:28.510
Thank you very much.

